{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28b877bdbffeT3wTjyt3WtTnYt","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d747884a1001Ez6voGqVDRTWXr","parts":[{"id":"prt_d7478963c0015T8MJFZxy7ULEz","messageID":"msg_d747884a1001Ez6voGqVDRTWXr","sessionID":"ses_28b877bdbffeT3wTjyt3WtTnYt","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_9efea7ce1a2d4b20832abbf3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # plotnine <img width=\"20%\" align=\"right\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/logo-512.png?raw=true\">\n2: \n3: [![Release](https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/plotnine.svg)](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/plotnine)\n4: [![License](https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/plotnine.svg)](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/plotnine)\n5: [![DOI](https://zenodo.org/badge/89276692.svg)](https://zenodo.org/badge/latestdoi/89276692)\n6: [![Build Status](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/workflows/build/badge.svg?branch=main)](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/actions?query=branch%3Amain+workflow%3A%22build%22)\n7: [![Coverage](https://codecov.io/github/has2k1/plotnine/coverage.svg?branch=main)](https://codecov.io/github/has2k1/plotnine?branch=main)\n8: \n9: plotnine is an implementation of a *grammar of graphics* in Python\n10: based on [ggplot2](https://github.com/tidyverse/ggplot2).\n11: The grammar allows you to compose plots by explicitly mapping variables in a\n12: dataframe to the visual characteristics (position, color, size etc.) of objects that make up the plot.\n13: \n14: Plotting with a *grammar of graphics* is powerful. Custom (and otherwise\n15: complex) plots are easy to think about and build incrementally, while the\n16: simple plots remain simple to create.\n17: \n18: To learn more about how to use plotnine, check out the\n19: [documentation](https://plotnine.org). Since plotnine\n20: has an API similar to ggplot2, where it lacks in coverage the\n21: [ggplot2 documentation](http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/index.html)\n22: may be helpful.\n23: \n24: \n25: ## Example\n26: \n27: ```python\n28: from plotnine import *\n29: from plotnine.data import mtcars\n30: ```\n31: \n32: Building a complex plot piece by piece.\n33: \n34: 1. Scatter plot\n35: \n36:    ```python\n37:    (\n38:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\"))\n39:        + geom_point()\n40:    )\n41:    ```\n42: \n43:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-1.png?raw=true\">\n44: \n45: 2. Scatter plot colored according some variable\n46: \n47:    ```python\n48:    (\n49:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\", color=\"factor(gear)\"))\n50:        + geom_point()\n51:    )\n52:    ```\n53: \n54:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-2.png?raw=true\">\n55: \n56: 3. Scatter plot colored according some variable and\n57:    smoothed with a linear model with confidence intervals.\n58: \n59:    ```python\n60:    (\n61:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\", color=\"factor(gear)\"))\n62:        + geom_point()\n63:        + stat_smooth(method=\"lm\")\n64:    )\n65:    ```\n66: \n67:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-3.png?raw=true\">\n68: \n69: 4. Scatter plot colored according some variable,\n70:    smoothed with a linear model with confidence intervals and\n71:    plotted on separate panels.\n72: \n73:    ```python\n74:    (\n75:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\", color=\"factor(gear)\"))\n76:        + geom_point()\n77:        + stat_smooth(method=\"lm\")\n78:        + facet_wrap(\"gear\")\n79:    )\n80:    ```\n81: \n82:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-4.png?raw=true\">\n83: \n84: 5. Adjust the themes\n85: \n86: \n87:    I) Make it playful\n88: \n89:    ```python\n90:    (\n91:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\", color=\"factor(gear)\"))\n92:        + geom_point()\n93:        + stat_smooth(method=\"lm\")\n94:        + facet_wrap(\"gear\")\n95:        + theme_xkcd()\n96:    )\n97:    ```\n98: \n99:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-5.png?raw=true\">\n100: \n101:    II) Or professional\n102: \n103:    ```python\n104:    (\n105:        ggplot(mtcars, aes(\"wt\", \"mpg\", color=\"factor(gear)\"))\n106:        + geom_point()\n107:        + stat_smooth(method=\"lm\")\n108:        + facet_wrap(\"gear\")\n109:        + theme_tufte()\n110:    )\n111:    ```\n112: \n113:    <img width=\"90%\" align=\"center\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/readme-image-5alt.png?raw=true\">\n114: \n115: ## Installation\n116: \n117: Official release\n118: \n119: ```console\n120: # Using pip\n121: $ pip install plotnine             # 1. should be sufficient for most\n122: $ pip install 'plotnine[extra]'    # 2. includes extra/optional packages\n123: $ pip install 'plotnine[test]'     # 3. testing\n124: $ pip install 'plotnine[doc]'      # 4. generating docs\n125: $ pip install 'plotnine[dev]'      # 5. development (making releases)\n126: $ pip install 'plotnine[all]'      # 6. everything\n127: \n128: # Or using conda\n129: $ conda install -c conda-forge plotnine\n130: \n131: # Or using pixi\n132: $ pixi init name-of-my-project\n133: $ cd name-of-my-project\n134: $ pixi add python plotnine\n135: ```\n136: \n137: Development version\n138: \n139: ```console\n140: $ pip install git+https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine.git\n141: ```\n142: \n143: ## Contributing\n144: \n145: Our documentation could use some examples, but we are looking for something\n146: a little bit special. We have two criteria:\n147: \n148: 1. Simple looking plots that otherwise require a trick or two.\n149: 2. Plots that are part of a data analytic narrative. That is, they provide\n150:    some form of clarity showing off the `geom`, `stat`, ... at their\n151:    differential best.\n152: \n153: If you come up with something that meets those criteria, we would love to\n154: see it. See [plotnine-examples](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine-examples).\n155: \n156: If you discover a bug checkout the [issues](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/issues)\n157: if it has not been reported, yet please file an issue.\n158: \n159: And if you can fix a bug, your contribution is welcome.\n160: \n161: Testing\n162: -------\n163: \n164: Plotnine has tests that generate images which are compared to baseline images known\n165: to be correct. There may be small differences in the text rendering that throw off the\n166: image comparisons, and the tests allow some very small differences.\n\n(End of file - total 166 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# plotnine <img width=\"20%\" align=\"right\" src=\"https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/blob/logos/doc/images/logo-512.png?raw=true\">\n\n[![Release](https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/plotnine.svg)](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/plotnine)\n[![License](https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/plotnine.svg)](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/plotnine)\n[![DOI](https://zenodo.org/badge/89276692.svg)](https://zenodo.org/badge/latestdoi/89276692)\n[![Build Status](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/workflows/build/badge.svg?branch=main)](https://github.com/has2k1/plotnine/actions?query=branch%3Amain+workflow%3A%22build%22)\n[![Coverage](https://codecov.io/github/has2k1/plotnine/coverage.svg?branch=main)](https://codecov.io/github/has2k1/plotnine?branch=main)\n\nplotnine is an implementation of a *grammar of graphics* in Python\nbased on [ggplot2](https://github.com/tidyverse/ggplot2).\nThe grammar allows you to compose plots by explicitly mapping variables in a\ndataframe to the visual characteristics (position, color, size etc.) of objects that make up the plot.\n\nPlotting with a *grammar of graphics* is powerful. Custom (and otherwise\ncomplex) plots are easy to think about and build incrementally, while the\nsimple plots remain simple to create.\n\nTo learn more about how to use plotnine, check out the\n[documentation](https://plotnine.org). Since plotnine\nhas an API similar to ggplot2, where it lacks in coverage the","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.md","time":{"start":1775775553507,"end":1775775553516}}}]}
